I am working on `sharp node module` to process JPEG images.

As explained in [this so question], I was struggling with the use of buffers in sharp image processing.

After going through sharp documentation, I realised that sharp objects are duplex streams.

Thus I thought of making use of streams instead of buffers to solve the memory consumption issue.

I ended up creating [this POC] that makes use of streams to read and process a 30 Mb jPG file.

However, I couldn&#39;t get any performance improvements. 


----------


POC Implementation
----------------

The POC creates a custom transform and writable stream to calculate the size of sharp image.

The final usage goes like this - **`Sharp Input Stream` | `Custom Transform Stream` | `Writable Stream`**

Folowing snippets explains it in detail -

**Sharp Input Stream**

    const imageFilePath = readFileSync(&quot;./30mb.jpg&quot;);
    let image = sharp(imageFilePath);

**Custom Transform Stream**

    class SizeCalculator extends Transform {
        constructor(options) {
            super(options);
            this.size = 0;
            this.count = 0;
        }
        _transform(chunk, encoding, callback) {
            console.log(++this.count); // count the chunks processed
            chunk &amp;&amp; chunk.length &amp;&amp; (this.size += chunk.length);
            callback();
        }
        _flush(callback) {
            this.push(this.size.toString());
            callback();
        }
    }

**Writable Stream**

    class ImageSize extends Writable {
        constructor(options) {
            super(options);
            this.size = 0;
        }
        _write(chunk, encoding, callback) {
            this.size = chunk.toString();
            callback();
        }
    }

**Usage**

    let image = sharp(imageFilePath);; // sharp image
    const sizeTransform = new SizeCalculator(); // transform stream
    const imageSize = new ImageSize(); // readable stream
    imageSize.on(&quot;finish&quot;, () =&gt; console.log(imageSize.size)); // listen to finish event
    image.pipe(sizeTransform).pipe(imageSize); // readable | transform | writable


----------

## Findings ##

In transform stream, I am counting the number of chunks required to process 30 Mb Image

As per the stream APIs, normal chunk size is 65536

However, in this case only one chunk serves the entire 30 Mb image

**And this is where the problem is. Use of streams becomes useless as stream is holding entire file in memory at once.**

